|> theorem
    number=1
    category=analysis

    **Theorem 1.** For any continuous function $f: [a,b] \to \mathbb{R}$,
    there exists $c \in [a,b]$ such that

    $$f(c) = \frac{1}{b-a} \int_a^b f(x) \, dx$$

    This is the Mean Value Theorem for integrals.

    Proof outline:
    1. Let $F(x) = \int_a^x f(t) \, dt$
    2. Then $F'(x) = f(x)$ by the Fundamental Theorem
    3. Apply MVT to $F$ on $[a,b]$: $F(b) - F(a) = F'(c)(b-a) = f(c)(b-a)$

